"# Appendix F — How this book maps to Book of ML

Book of Code and Book of ML are companions. If you read them both,
you will understand what a computer is and what a language model is,
built up from nothing in each case.

- **Book of Code** teaches you what a computer is. Ishango bone →
  transistors → gates → CPU → OS → internet → LLM. Hardware and
  systems, ending at the modern LLM ecosystem.
- **Book of ML** teaches you what a language model is. Numbers →
  vectors → matrices → neurons → attention → transformer → LLM. Math
  and code, ending at a runnable tiny LLM in your Motoi REPL.

Read Code first. It gives you the vocabulary (CPU, memory, ALU, loop,
state machine) that Book of ML will assume. Then read ML.

## The chapter alignment

Both books have 16 chapters. Roughly:

```
   Book of Code             Book of ML
   -----------              ----------
    1  Tallies              1  Numbers and tensors
    2  Boolean logic        2  Vectors and dot product
    3  Electricity          3  Matrices
    4  Switch to gate       4  Functions of functions
    5  Gates in Scheme      5  What is a model
    6  Half/full adder      6  Gradient descent
    7  4-bit adder          7  Single neuron
    8  Flip-flops           8  A layer, then two
    9  Registers            9  Backpropagation
   10  State machines      10  Training loop
   11  ALU                 11  Tokens and embeddings
   12  CPU                 12  Attention
   13  Memory hierarchy    13  Transformer block
   14  Assembly to Scheme  14  Positional encoding
   15  OS and networks     15  Stacking + tokenization
   16  Cloud and LLMs      16  The tiny LLM
```

They are not one-to-one, but they follow the same rhythm: small
building blocks in the early chapters, composition in the middle,
system-level integration at the end.

## Where they touch

There are three places where the two books directly touch each
other.

### 1. The transformer forward pass (Code Ch 16, ML Ch 12-16)

Book of Code chapter 16 describes the transformer as *the current
architecture that runs Claude, Gemini, GPT, and DeepSeek*. It does
not build one. Book of ML chapters 12 through 16 build one, step by
step, in Motoi Scheme. If you want the code, go to Book of ML. If you
want the historical arc that led to the transformer, stay in Book of
Code.

### 2. Memory hierarchy and LLM inference (Code Ch 13, ML Ch 16)

Book of Code chapter 13 explains why memory bandwidth matters. Book
of ML chapter 16 explains why memory bandwidth is what makes LLM
serving expensive. The two chapters compose: the tiny LLM in the ML
book actually fits in L1 cache. Real LLMs don't. This is why real
LLMs need racks of GPUs. Same phenomenon; different scales.

### 3. Training loop and gradient descent (Code Appendix E, ML Ch 6, 10)

Book of Code Appendix E names the training loop as the
optimization loop that produces LLMs. Book of ML chapter 6 explains
gradient descent by hand. Book of ML chapter 10 wraps the gradient
descent inside a full training loop. Together the two coverage-slices
answer *what does 'training a model' actually mean, mechanically.*

## What Book of Code has that Book of ML doesn't

- Historical arc from prehistory forward.
- Electronics, gates, adders — the substrate.
- The CPU, ALU, and how instructions execute.
- Operating systems and networking context.
- ASCII diagrams of hardware structures.

## What Book of ML has that Book of Code doesn't

- Actual math: dot products, matrix multiplication, gradients.
- A working neural network built in Motoi Scheme.
- Attention as a soft lookup.
- The full transformer, block by block.
- A tiny LLM you can train on a paragraph and see finish a sentence.

## Reading order

**Beginner:** Code first, then ML. You need the substrate to
appreciate what the model is doing.

**Working programmer with LLM experience:** ML first, if you already
know computers well. Then Code if you want to see the substrate
worldview.

**Someone teaching a course:** interleave them. Chapter N of Code
paired with Chapter N of ML makes a nice unit. The correspondence
above is a rough guide.

## Cross-references from each book

The Book of Code chapter 16 mentions Book of ML as *the place to go
for the code-level view of a transformer.*

The Book of ML cover mentions *Book of Sick Composition and Book of
R7RS Recipes are the on-ramps* — the Scheme prerequisites. It also
mentions Motoi's runtime and math verb surface.

Neither book depends on the other for its own thread. They both
stand alone. But together they close the twenty-thousand-year arc
from the Ishango bone to the runnable tiny LLM on your laptop.

## Beyond the two books

If you finish both and want more:

- **Book of Computing** (in this repo) — the shorter, teachable
  version of the same substrate arc, told through Motoi's beloved
  old machines (Speak & Spell, C64, Atari 800, Apple IIc, Amiga).
- **Book of Language Ancestors** — biographies of the people who
  built Scheme and the languages it came from (Church, Turing,
  McCarthy, Steele, Sussman, Landin, Strachey, Knuth, Dijkstra,
  Liskov, Ritchie, Thompson, Kay, Hopper, Lovelace, Babbage,
  Shannon).
- **SICP** — Abelson, Sussman, Sussman. The classic. Builds Scheme
  in Scheme.
- **Petzold, *Code*** — the shape inspiration for this book.
- **Feynman, *Lectures on Computation***.
- See Appendix G for the full reading list.

## Composition

The two-book pair composes. Read them together and:

- You know what a computer is.
- You know what a language model is.
- You know why LLMs run so slowly on cheap hardware.
- You know why they cost so much to train.
- You know how to write Motoi Scheme code that touches all the
  layers, from a full adder to a tiny transformer.

That is a lot for a rainy afternoon. That is also why Motoi thinks
these two books are the anchor books. They close the loop.

## The loop appears

The whole arc of these two books is a loop. Motoi is a language.
Books teach the language. Learners write programs. Programs teach the
learners more. Learners write bigger programs. Some of them
eventually train language models. Language models help learners
write programs. Language models get better. Learners get better. And
around the loop again.

Motoi is a small link in that loop. Speak & Spell was a small link
in the same loop, forty years earlier. Both do one thing warmly and
deterministically. Both help a person feel mastery. Both are useful
without being the biggest thing on the block.

## Reading list

For the full list of recommended follow-on books, see Appendix G.
")
